WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.370 --> 00:00:05.589
&gt;&gt;Julie: Greetings, everybody. I'm Julie Wiskirchen
at the Authors@Google team in Santa Monica

00:00:05.589 --> 00:00:08.600
and we're extremely excited today to welcome
Molly Ringwald.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:17.810
[applause and cheering]

00:00:17.810 --> 00:00:22.260
Molly began her film career at the age of
13 with a Golden Globe nominated performance

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:27.890
in Paul Mazursky's, Tempest. In the 80s, she
starred in such beloved coming-of-age movies

00:00:27.890 --> 00:00:32.750
as Sixteen Candles, The Breakfast Club and
Pretty in Pink, then moved to Paris in '92

00:00:32.750 --> 00:00:38.010
and acted in such films as Seven Sundays and
King Lear, a screen adaptation directed by

00:00:38.010 --> 00:00:41.079
French film legend, Jean-Luc Godard.

00:00:41.079 --> 00:00:45.260
On TV you can currently see her starring in
ABC Family's, "The Secret Life of the American

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:50.699
Teenager." She also appeared in the series,
"Townies" and Steven King's, "The Stand."

00:00:50.699 --> 00:00:56.539
Her theatre credits include playing Sally
Bowles in Cabaret on Broadway, a London Stage

00:00:56.539 --> 00:01:00.899
Production of When Harry Met Sally, and the
Tony nominated Enchanted April.

00:01:00.899 --> 00:01:05.890
Off Broadway, she was in Tick, Tickâ€¦Boom,
and in a national tour of Sweet Charity. And

00:01:05.890 --> 00:01:10.190
today she's here to talk to us about her brand
new book, which is entitled, "Getting the

00:01:10.190 --> 00:01:15.050
Pretty Back: Friendship, Family and Finding
the Perfect Lipstick." So please join me in

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:16.080
welcoming Molly Ringwald.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:18.970
[applause and cheering]

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:22.830
&gt;&gt;Molly: Thank you. Hi.

00:01:22.830 --> 00:01:24.760
&gt;&gt;audience: Hi.

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:31.400
&gt;&gt;Molly: It's so great to be here. I feel
like I really fit the whole color scheme.

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:36.030
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Molly: I'm very Google. All right. I think

00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:41.540
I'd like to start out with, usually when I
read from my book, I like to start out with

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:46.530
the first chapter because I-, I like people
to understand that when I'm talking about

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:53.240
"pretty," it's not so much of a physical thing
as it is an attitude and a state of mind.

00:01:53.240 --> 00:01:57.420
So, the, the first chapter is called, "Isn't
It Pretty to Think So?"

00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:59.410
[reads from book]

00:01:59.410 --> 00:02:04.180
"Early on during my first pregnancy, a female
acquaintance off mine told me, 'You better

00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:09.609
hope she isn't a girl 'cause she'll suck the
pretty out of you.' I sort of laughed. Sort

00:02:09.609 --> 00:02:14.629
of. In a few short weeks, I found out that
the baby was a girl. A few weeks after that,

00:02:14.629 --> 00:02:21.519
I was absolutely sure that the woman was right.
I was not a particularly attractive pregnant

00:02:21.519 --> 00:02:22.519
person.

00:02:22.519 --> 00:02:26.659
"Every woman I know has wanted to be beautifully
pregnant; the type of Cover Girl pregnant

00:02:26.659 --> 00:02:30.939
where you can't tell from behind. It's only
until you turn and reveal the perfect bump

00:02:30.939 --> 00:02:36.409
hovering over your Manolos that you are with
child. Me? I blew up like a water balloon,

00:02:36.409 --> 00:02:41.739
thanks to a semi-common ailment, preeclampsia,
and a troubling, powerful fondness for Macho

00:02:41.739 --> 00:02:48.170
Nachos. The freckles on my face decided to
band together and form a pigment block party

00:02:48.170 --> 00:02:53.030
and my ankles swelled as if I'd been stung
by a hive of particularly vindictive bees.

00:02:53.030 --> 00:02:57.209
"On the day my daughter, Matilda, was born,
as I tried to tie up loose ends before heading

00:02:57.209 --> 00:03:02.139
into the labor room, I was asked to participate
in a Maternity Gap ad, which I was obviously

00:03:02.139 --> 00:03:06.450
unable to do. When I hung up the phone and
told my husband and friend, Victoria, the

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:11.181
nurse on-call chimed in, 'That's funny. A
Gap ad? You look like the Michelin Man!'

00:03:11.181 --> 00:03:12.819
[laughter]

00:03:12.819 --> 00:03:16.969
"My husband, friend and I were shocked into
silence. The nurse took this to mean that

00:03:16.969 --> 00:03:20.079
we hadn't heard her and felt compelled to
repeat her insight.

00:03:20.079 --> 00:03:21.209
[laughter]

00:03:21.209 --> 00:03:25.359
'You look like the Michelin Man,' she snorted.
It wasn't until she went in for the third

00:03:25.359 --> 00:03:27.909
time that Victoria snapped, 'Yeah, we got
it.'

00:03:27.909 --> 00:03:29.249
[laughter]

00:03:29.249 --> 00:03:33.489
"In the months after I delivered Matilda,
I would catch glimpses of myself in the mirror

00:03:33.489 --> 00:03:39.180
each time thinking the same thing, 'Is that
me?' I couldn't get over the heft of my body.

00:03:39.180 --> 00:03:43.340
I would breastfeed my daughter and look down
in horror to find that my breasts were larger

00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:44.340
than her head.

00:03:44.340 --> 00:03:45.810
[laughter]

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:50.549
"My husband came home from work one day to
discover me in the bedroom dissolved in tears.'It's

00:03:50.549 --> 00:03:56.230
true, it's true.' 'What's true?' he asked,
alarmed. 'She got it all. She sucked the pretty

00:03:56.230 --> 00:03:57.230
out of me.'

00:03:57.230 --> 00:03:58.230
[laughter]

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:01.900
"I'm sure I'm not the only woman who has felt
this way and obviously it isn't only motherhood

00:04:01.900 --> 00:04:06.370
that can give you this feeling; it can be
a relationship gone south, a stressful job,

00:04:06.370 --> 00:04:10.900
weight gain. What makes it so disturbing when
it is motherhood, however, is the completely

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:15.799
irrational feeling that your loss is someone
else's gain; something that is so associated

00:04:15.799 --> 00:04:21.849
with something so wonderful: the giving of
life. It's the ultimate bittersweet sensation.

00:04:21.849 --> 00:04:26.940
"It seems to me that there is a moment when
women are no longer defined as pretty. It's

00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:30.840
hard to know when exactly it happens, but
suddenly you notice it. You are beautiful,

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:38.860
unique, handsome (if you're unlucky), or interesting;
pretty is a word that is reserved for the

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:44.500
young. At some point you are expected to relinquish
the word like an Olympic torch. If you were

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:48.379
ever called pretty to begin with, you know
that there's a definite time limit imposed

00:04:48.379 --> 00:04:49.460
upon the word.

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:53.910
"You could say that it has the longevity of
the career of an ice skater or ballerina.

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:58.680
You get to dance, swan-like, a few times,
then you're expected to teach it. What is

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:05.199
pretty anyway? Not just beauty. It's an attitude
toward life, a frame of mind, a lightness,

00:05:05.199 --> 00:05:11.199
even a frivolousness; it's attractive and
charming, yet also naive. It's endearing particularly

00:05:11.199 --> 00:05:15.639
because it's so innocent, because it seems
to disregard, or simply be unaware of, all

00:05:15.639 --> 00:05:19.949
the things in the world; the experiences,
the people, the accidents that increasingly

00:05:19.949 --> 00:05:24.919
defy and deny the sense of giddy hopefulness.
When I told a friend I was writing a book

00:05:24.919 --> 00:05:28.120
called 'Getting the Pretty Back,' she asked,
'Why don't you call it Getting the Beauty

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:32.870
Back? That's a better title.'
'But beauty isn't what I'm talking about.

00:05:32.870 --> 00:05:37.770
Prettiness is inside every woman. It's a feeling,
a sense of self that never entirely leaves,

00:05:37.770 --> 00:05:41.660
it's always there.'
"I remember at my daughter's baptism, which

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:45.670
we had in Greece where my husband's parents
live, watching my mother-in-law dancing at

00:05:45.670 --> 00:05:50.220
the after party at four in the morning, as
she spun I could see the village girl she

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:56.340
had been 50 years earlier in every light,
joyful step. It was moving and it was inspiring

00:05:56.340 --> 00:06:01.979
and it was also, the best part, completely,
carelessly normal. She wasn't thinking about

00:06:01.979 --> 00:06:06.729
it. She wasn't pretending. She was just doing
what felt right. I watched her turning her

00:06:06.729 --> 00:06:11.069
wrists and hands in time with the music with
such confidence and grace thinking to myself,'

00:06:11.069 --> 00:06:15.349
She's so pretty.'
"Getting the pretty back is about getting

00:06:15.349 --> 00:06:18.979
in touch with your essential self; the part
of you that knows what you really want, that

00:06:18.979 --> 00:06:24.259
takes risks, that isn't scared away by all
the things that can and have gone wrong. It's

00:06:24.259 --> 00:06:28.629
the part of you that runs around in summer,
holding your sandals in your hand. It's remembering

00:06:28.629 --> 00:06:33.030
the girl you were at 15 who did double flips
off the high-dive, the girl who laughed and

00:06:33.030 --> 00:06:36.979
squealed with your best friend while you huddled
together in the bathroom double-piercing your

00:06:36.979 --> 00:06:39.460
ear with a needle and a potato.

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:40.460
[laughter]

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:44.509
"Being pretty can be about style or outer
beauty, true. But on a deeper, more fundamental

00:06:44.509 --> 00:06:48.819
level, it's about learning to take care of
yourself again. Style is the first and easiest

00:06:48.819 --> 00:06:53.919
step to reminding yourself, and the world,
that you matter. Too often, after kids, after

00:06:53.919 --> 00:06:59.009
years in and out of relationships, we settle.
We stop paying attention to ourselves. Everyone

00:06:59.009 --> 00:07:03.770
else's needs come first. We'd love to try
a yoga class or see a movie with a friend,

00:07:03.770 --> 00:07:07.389
or visit a country that we've never been to,
but before that can happen we have all these

00:07:07.389 --> 00:07:11.560
other responsibilities: the car payments,
the mortgage, the dental appointments, the

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:14.770
carpools, the birthday parties, the work functions.

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:18.950
"At times they can make you feel as if adulthood
is nothing more than a series of tasks to

00:07:18.950 --> 00:07:24.009
be completed. And I'm not advocating trying
to recapture your youth, mostly because it

00:07:24.009 --> 00:07:29.870
isn't possible, but secondly because you shouldn't
want to. Our life experience, after all, is

00:07:29.870 --> 00:07:34.789
what makes us interesting, smarter, more confident
and formidable. But being all those things

00:07:34.789 --> 00:07:39.710
shouldn't preclude being whimsical, light,
flirty and fun. At heart, prettiness is a

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:43.720
state of mind; it's a way of looking at things.
A way of looking at ourselves. It's just one

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:49.409
thread of the tapestry that makes us up, but
it's an all too often neglected thread. Luckily,

00:07:49.409 --> 00:07:52.890
it isn't so hard to get the pretty back as
I rediscovered again while writing this book.

00:07:52.890 --> 00:07:57.280
I spent a lot of time searching through my
past, remembering the good and bad, and finding

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.849
out what got me to where I am now and I invite
you to do the same. Whether it's reconnecting

00:08:01.849 --> 00:08:06.069
with friends that you miss or remembering
how much you used to love to dance to Bananarama

00:08:06.069 --> 00:08:07.531
in the living room by yourself--

00:08:07.531 --> 00:08:08.700
[laughter]

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:12.219
getting back in touch with the pretty girl
that you once were, just might make you realize

00:08:12.219 --> 00:08:14.419
that she isn't so far from the woman that
you are today."

00:08:14.419 --> 00:08:17.400
[applause]

00:08:17.400 --> 00:08:23.370
Thank you.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:28.310
I wanted to read you one other part and, and
I've been talking with my husband back there,

00:08:28.310 --> 00:08:33.740
who just graduated from Stanford on Saturday,
just got his MBA.

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:36.510
[applause, clapping, cheering]

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:43.409
Go Panio! So we were talking in the car about
what to read and I didn't, honestly, I didn't

00:08:43.409 --> 00:08:48.510
expect so many men to be here. And I'm really
thrilled, so I'm trying to think of, you know,

00:08:48.510 --> 00:08:53.730
the book is obviously written more for women,
but not to say that men can't get something

00:08:53.730 --> 00:08:59.990
out of it, too. So, I don't, I don't know.
There's, there's nine chapters to, to the

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:05.840
book and they're all sort of about what it
means, to me, to be a woman. So I just try

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:11.130
to think about, you know, wh-, what's important
to me, and so there's a style chapter, there's

00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:13.800
a food chapter, there's a fitness chapter,
there's even a hair chapter.

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:14.800
[laughter]

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:21.850
So, I decided to read something I, I haven't
actually read at other book readings and it's

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:27.170
part of the style chapter, which is called,
"It Woman," which is kind of the genesis of

00:09:27.170 --> 00:09:33.450
the book. I decided, when I was turning 40
years old, that every stylish book seemed

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:38.300
to be about "It" girls rather than "It" women.
So, I wanted to write a book about being an

00:09:38.300 --> 00:09:44.260
"It" woman. And so, so here's the, the beginning
of Chapter Two, "It Woman."

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:45.760
[reads from book]

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:50.550
"When I was seven years old, I was a tall,
leggy kid with short, shaggy hair and permanently

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:55.820
stubbed toes and for a good deal of time,
I sported a woman's stocking, my mothers,

00:09:55.820 --> 00:10:01.980
attached to the top of my head with two precisely
criss-crossed bobby pins. This seemed to be--"

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:02.980
[noise interference]

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:03.980
What's that?

00:10:03.980 --> 00:10:04.980
&gt;&gt;team member: ok

00:10:04.980 --> 00:10:06.250
&gt;&gt;Molly: Oh.

00:10:06.250 --> 00:10:08.440
[continues to read]

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:13.150
"This seemed to be, in my seven year old brain,
the best solution as to how to exist in California

00:10:13.150 --> 00:10:18.160
in the 70s with a gorgeous, blue-eyed older
sister with long, blonde hair. I was sure

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:22.400
that she knew how it tortured me as I lay
on the bed and watched her brush her long,

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:27.150
straight trusses and then flip it back over
to have it land on her back as if in slow

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:32.690
motion. I was memorized by the perfection
of it. It was the perfect color, the perfect

00:10:32.690 --> 00:10:34.639
weight; it even smelled nice.

00:10:34.639 --> 00:10:38.100
"Farah Fawcett shampoo. Which I'm pretty sure
it was just Herbal Essence with a picture

00:10:38.100 --> 00:10:43.769
of Farah stuck on the bottle. I asked my mother
if I could grow my hair out like my sisters.

00:10:43.769 --> 00:10:47.279
'Maybe later,' she'd tell me. 'This time we'll
cut it short and you'll see, it'll grow in

00:10:47.279 --> 00:10:52.620
thicker.' This lie, handed down from the ages,
clearly senseless, and yet somehow at that

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:56.610
age, irrefutable, and anyway, who doesn't
want thicker hair? So, off to the barber I'd

00:10:56.610 --> 00:11:01.350
go where they'd chop off my honey colored
wisps and fashion my hair into a boys cut.

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:05.851
'A pixie,' my mom would say. 'What's his name?'
everyone else would say.

00:11:05.851 --> 00:11:06.990
[laughter]

00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:11.100
"In our neighborhood, in every direction out
of our cul-de-sac, there was a home that housed

00:11:11.100 --> 00:11:15.220
a set of siblings. Joanie and Jennifer to
the left of us, Laurie and Lisa to the right,

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:19.660
and Karen and Krista in the middle, across
the street. Not one of which, incidentally,

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:24.630
had anything short of shoulder length hair.
Our games mostly consisted of freeze tag and

00:11:24.630 --> 00:11:28.760
cartoon tag and I could occasionally corral
them into taking part in a backyard vaudeville

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:33.620
show. I'd copied out scenes from classic Abbot
and Costello sketches from a local show that

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:37.640
my brother and sister and I performed in on
the weekends. I would direct them to the proper

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:42.930
timing and sometimes have to explain the joke.
'Yeah, you see, his name is Who and see the

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:44.910
other guy doesn't get it.'

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:48.180
"This would keep us occupied until the ice
cream truck or some other distraction came

00:11:48.180 --> 00:11:52.490
along and then home for dinner. Then, one
day, while playing inside the house, rummaging

00:11:52.490 --> 00:11:56.620
through my mother's things, I came across
a long ponytail curled up in a hat box that

00:11:56.620 --> 00:12:01.170
I was pretty sure wasn't real, but nevertheless
intrigued me almost as though it were a living,

00:12:01.170 --> 00:12:05.640
breathing thing. Treating it with reverence,
I carefully presented it to my mother for

00:12:05.640 --> 00:12:10.480
explanation. I don't even think that it matched
my mother's hair color. 'Oh, it's a fall,'

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:15.410
she said. 'We used to wear those all the time
a few years ago. Nobody wears them anymore.'

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:19.200
This information I accepted gladly since it
basically gave me free reign to claim the

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:24.550
thing as my own. I would attach it to my head
and no one would be able to pry it loose.

00:12:24.550 --> 00:12:27.740
Unfortunately, there was precious little to
attach it to.

00:12:27.740 --> 00:12:31.459
"Every time I thought I had it fixed, the
second I attempted to copy my sister's hair

00:12:31.459 --> 00:12:36.700
swing, that I'm sure she copied from Susan
Day, the flick from one shoulder to the other,

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:41.540
the hairpiece would fly across the room and
sail onto the floor. Apparently, this unhappy

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:45.790
event actually happened to a famous singer,
dancer, on Johnny Carson's, The Tonight Show,

00:12:45.790 --> 00:12:50.250
which my mother remembers helped deter her
from wearing the elaborate up do and they

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:52.560
were really going out of style anyway.

00:12:52.560 --> 00:12:56.690
"This did little to deter me until I had to
face the fact that as much as I loved this

00:12:56.690 --> 00:13:01.079
piece of hair and wanted it attached to me,
the thing had no interest in me, preferring

00:13:01.079 --> 00:13:06.250
to hibernate indefinitely in the hatbox. I
reasoned that the real problem was the weight

00:13:06.250 --> 00:13:10.860
of the hairpiece and if I could just find
a less weighty version, unfortunately, my

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:15.990
mother had not invested much in her hair accoutrement.
There were only two that I could find and

00:13:15.990 --> 00:13:19.510
one of them I figured was a Halloween wig
and of little interest, since it was a short,

00:13:19.510 --> 00:13:24.759
curly do that looked like it belonged to Bewitched's
Samantha's frisky cousin, Serena. But I did

00:13:24.759 --> 00:13:30.680
happen upon a pair of stockings, one for each
leg. While pantyhose were becoming more commonplace,

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:35.060
my mother still owned the old-fashioned, singular
nylons, which along with the fall, I never

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:39.390
saw her wear. The thought occurred to me that
it was about the same length as the fall and

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:43.910
a much better color match. Two bobbies later,
I was in business.

00:13:43.910 --> 00:13:44.910
[laughter]

00:13:44.910 --> 00:13:48.050
"I flicked my head around and admired my handiwork.
Then I ventured out into the neighborhood.

00:13:48.050 --> 00:13:49.360
[laughter]

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:53.350
"My friends make no mention of my new hairdo,
if they even noticed they didn't' let on.

00:13:53.350 --> 00:13:57.720
I was filled with a combination of relief
and disappointment. Relief that I wasn't about

00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:01.660
to be made fun of mercilessly, I still can't
quite believe it. I don't know if it was the

00:14:01.660 --> 00:14:07.069
age or the place, the fact that I had exceptionally
kind friends, and disappointment because couldn't

00:14:07.069 --> 00:14:12.399
they see I had long hair? Then a couple of
days later, I noticed Jennifer sporting a

00:14:12.399 --> 00:14:13.501
black stocking on her head.

00:14:13.501 --> 00:14:14.501
[laughter]

00:14:14.501 --> 00:14:19.250
"Soon, all the girls tried it out, even pinning
their own hair up in order to show the stocking

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:23.790
hanging down. Joanie went so far as to put
pantyhose on her head, but we all agreed that

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:24.790
was ridiculous.

00:14:24.790 --> 00:14:25.790
[laughter]

00:14:25.790 --> 00:14:29.960
"It was at that time when I realized that
I had set a trend. I had an idea that was

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:35.579
different. I executed it and I watched it
catch on. It was magical the way we all entered

00:14:35.579 --> 00:14:40.440
into a tacit understanding that stockings
on our head was cool, even when the evidence

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:44.870
should have clearly showed us otherwise. I
think I discovered at that moment that fashion

