&gt;&gt;member female: [inaudible]

00:15:57.790 --> 00:15:59.630
&gt;&gt;Molly: Any other questions?

00:15:59.630 --> 00:16:05.000
&gt;&gt;memberfemale2: I have one. I actually saw
you when I was living in New York, in Tick,

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.899
Tickâ€¦Boom and which I thought was great
and it was all about kind of the turning 30

00:16:09.899 --> 00:16:14.459
and, and how to deal with that milestone and
now your books about turning 40, so I was

00:16:14.459 --> 00:16:18.649
wondering if you thought back to that musical
or if you saw any parallels between those

00:16:18.649 --> 00:16:19.649
two.

00:16:19.649 --> 00:16:26.839
&gt;&gt;Molly: I actually, I haven't made the connection,
but it, it's, it is, I think, a similar feeling.

00:16:26.839 --> 00:16:33.879
I think for women, 40 is even more. I mean,
40 is really the moment when you can no longer

00:16:33.879 --> 00:16:39.460
call yourself an ingÃ©nue in, in any realm
at all, you know? And, and you know, most

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:44.870
people, by the time they're 40, ha-, you know,
have kids and you know, or, you know. I mean,

00:16:44.870 --> 00:16:50.589
I had my kids later than, than most people
do. I have a six year old daughter and eleven

00:16:50.589 --> 00:16:54.459
month old twins. Yeah, they're so cute.

00:16:54.459 --> 00:16:55.459
[laughter]

00:16:55.459 --> 00:17:00.459
But, you know, 40 is really that age that
I think it's not so much that you feel different,

00:17:00.459 --> 00:17:07.770
it's that, that you feel that everyone sees
you differently. I was doing, when I was on

00:17:07.770 --> 00:17:13.199
my book tour, I was doing "Regis and Kelly"
and she, she actually had a really great comment

00:17:13.199 --> 00:17:18.439
that I think she heard from someone else,
but it seems that at 39, everyone says to

00:17:18.439 --> 00:17:22.839
you, "Are you ok? You look so tired." And
then you turn 40 and they go, "Wow, you look

00:17:22.839 --> 00:17:23.880
great for 40." You know?

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:24.880
[laughter]

00:17:24.880 --> 00:17:30.440
It's like, suddenly the perception completely
changes. But yeah, I mean, Tick, Tickâ€¦Boom

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:35.730
was very similar. I think, I think Jonathan
Larson really felt that way because his, his

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:42.440
career really hadn't taken off yet. He was
still the "starving artist" and I think, for

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:47.809
him, he felt that that's acceptable. You know,
we all put these numbers and, you know, they,

00:17:47.809 --> 00:17:49.340
they don't really mean anything.

00:17:49.340 --> 00:17:53.260
It's just what we put on ourselves, you know?
When you're, when you're creating, when you,

00:17:53.260 --> 00:17:57.330
when you're, when you're an artist, it's like
you, you should have arrived already by the

00:17:57.330 --> 00:18:03.590
time you're 30 and I think that was the pressure
he felt is that, that after 30 it was like,

00:18:03.590 --> 00:18:08.919
ok now he's gonna have to get a real job,
you know? And I think that, that this happens

00:18:08.919 --> 00:18:13.461
all the time. I think, you know, I'm, I remember
turning 25 and feeling that, you know, oh

00:18:13.461 --> 00:18:14.770
my God, I was so old, you know?

00:18:14.770 --> 00:18:16.490
[laughter]

00:18:16.490 --> 00:18:19.980
You know, it's just, i-, i-, it happens all
the time, you know? You're a teenager and

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:24.870
all you can think about is, is being 21 and
then after 21 its like, "Oh my God, I'm so

00:18:24.870 --> 00:18:29.541
old!" You know? It's gonna happen. I think,
I think I'm gonna look back on turning 40

00:18:29.541 --> 00:18:38.320
and feel like I was a baby, you know? So,
any other questions? Yes.

00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:43.820
&gt;&gt;membermale3: Steven King's, The Stand, is
a marathon of a book by any means, so when

00:18:43.820 --> 00:18:46.400
you're preparing or any time since, have you
read the book?

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:53.250
&gt;&gt;Molly: I read the book while I was making
the movie, actually. I hadn't read it prior

00:18:53.250 --> 00:18:59.760
to, to doing, I read the script. And the,
the script, the, or I should say the teleplay,

00:18:59.760 --> 00:19:04.120
because it was, it was a television movie;
I think was a pretty faithful adaptation.

00:19:04.120 --> 00:19:08.679
Because I remember as I was reading the book,
I felt like I had just read it, you know?

00:19:08.679 --> 00:19:17.429
Because I just read this incredibly long teleplay.
But, you know, usually, I mean I think, I,

00:19:17.429 --> 00:19:23.460
I prepare differently for each project. Sometimes
I feel like I, I understand the character

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:27.250
completely. I mean, like for instance, all
the John Hughes movies I did, there was not

00:19:27.250 --> 00:19:32.039
a lot of research that went into those parts,
you know? They were very similar to, to me,

00:19:32.039 --> 00:19:37.010
or to somebody that I knew, but then other
parts, obviously require more research.

00:19:37.010 --> 00:19:43.830
&gt;&gt;membermale3: So, I love the movie adaptation
and watching it is an effort in itself, so

00:19:43.830 --> 00:19:46.850
how was filming it? I mean, it, it's so long.

00:19:46.850 --> 00:19:53.380
&gt;Molly: It was really long. I had just moved
to France, actually and that was the first

00:19:53.380 --> 00:20:00.640
time I'd been back in America since I had
chosen to move to another country and I, I

00:20:00.640 --> 00:20:06.179
remember having a lot of, of down time and,
and constantly trying to, to get back to France,

00:20:06.179 --> 00:20:14.440
you know? So, it was, it was, it was such
a big, huge cast and, you know, I just, I

00:20:14.440 --> 00:20:19.960
mean I had most of my scenes with Gary Sinise
