00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:23.350
&gt;&gt;membermale3: Thanks.

00:20:23.350 --> 00:20:24.350
&gt;&gt;Molly: Sure. Yes.

00:20:24.350 --> 00:20:25.350
&gt;&gt;memberfemale4: You're one of these rare,
amazing performers whose career has spanned,

00:20:25.350 --> 00:20:26.350
you know, the stage, screen and television.
And I'd like you to talk a little bit about

00:20:26.350 --> 00:20:45.150
your approach to the different media. If there
is one you prefer, and if it sort of on a

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:46.150
project to project basis.

00:20:46.150 --> 00:20:52.400
&gt;&gt;Molly: That's a great question, thanks.
I don't prefer any, any of them, I think.

00:20:52.400 --> 00:20:56.490
I, I mean, I started out doing theatre so
I think theatre, so I think theater is a little

00:20:56.490 --> 00:21:03.780
bit like my first love and I've always felt
really comfortable on stage. And then I moved

00:21:03.780 --> 00:21:08.830
to film and I think I'm more known as a film
actress. I love the immediacy of television

00:21:08.830 --> 00:21:13.460
and I, and I love how many people you can
reach on television, you know?

00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:19.020
I, after I, I lived in France for all those
years, I came back to New York and I did almost

00:21:19.020 --> 00:21:24.930
exclusively theatre for about ten years and
I feel like, except for the people that happen

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:29.320
to be there at the time, nobody knows. It
was like I wasn't doing anything for, for

00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:34.270
ten years, you know? But, I mean, people that
were there, you know, they say me in all these

00:21:34.270 --> 00:21:37.402
plays and they thought, "Oh, I didn't know
you could sing, I didn't know you could dance,"

00:21:37.402 --> 00:21:41.520
you know? But then, it just, there's all these
people that it doesn't reach, you know?

00:21:41.520 --> 00:21:46.140
So, that doesn't mean that I don't love doing
it, but I, obviously when you work you love

00:21:46.140 --> 00:21:52.179
to, to be able to, to connect with people
and to reach people. So, I did all of that

00:21:52.179 --> 00:21:55.660
theatre and then I moved here and now I'm
on a television show and it, it always seems

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:59.909
like I love to go back and forth. I mean,
I would love to go back to New York and do,

00:21:59.909 --> 00:22:04.320
it's been, it's been a couple years now since
I've done a play. I would love to do it, you

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:07.669
know, especially with the Tony's last night,
I think, "Oh, my God, I love, I love doing

00:22:07.669 --> 00:22:11.740
theatre." You know, and I'd love to do more
films. I think it really just depends on the

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:16.740
project and I think that there's certain projects
that, that sort of lend themselves to a certain

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:20.920
medium. So, depends on the story. Yes?

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:29.040
&gt;&gt;memberfemale5: Did living around Parisian
women affect your sense of pretty? [inaudible]

00:22:29.040 --> 00:22:36.540
&gt;&gt;Molly: I feel like French women are, I mean,
they're, they're incredibly stylish. They

00:22:36.540 --> 00:22:38.299
seem to come out of the womb--

00:22:38.299 --> 00:22:39.299
[laughter]

00:22:39.299 --> 00:22:46.260
with an Hermes scarf sort of wrapped perfectly
around their neck. They just seem to have

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:52.730
an innate sense of style that I really think
comes from a sense of confidence, you know?

00:22:52.730 --> 00:22:58.910
When I was writing this book and going through
the editorial process, I did a word search

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:02.720
one day on the word "confidence" cause I wanted,
or "confident." I wanted to know how many

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:07.180
times I used that word and it was ridiculous.
I used that word like, 25 times, I used the

00:23:07.180 --> 00:23:11.480
word confident. But I think it really said
something about one of the themes of my book,

00:23:11.480 --> 00:23:17.230
which is how confidence, confidence in yourself,
is one of the most important things because

00:23:17.230 --> 00:23:20.730
if you don't have confidence in yourself,
no one is gonna have confidence in you. And

00:23:20.730 --> 00:23:26.220
it affects everything. It affects your style,
it affects the way that people listen to you,

00:23:26.220 --> 00:23:28.799
you know, it affects everything.

00:23:28.799 --> 00:23:33.271
So, I think that that's something and I don't
know exactly, i-, it's something that was

00:23:33.271 --> 00:23:37.990
very interesting to me figuring out where,
where French women come up with this sense

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:43.169
of confidence and I, I really do think it
has something to do with their culture. And

00:23:43.169 --> 00:23:48.240
it's something I hope to impart on, on, on
my children, my girls especially. You know,

00:23:48.240 --> 00:23:53.409
the feeling that they can do anything that
a man can do and in heels, backwards.

00:23:53.409 --> 00:23:56.130
[laughter]

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:57.160
Great question, though. Thank you.

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:02.721
&gt;&gt;Julie: Does anyone on the video conference
have questions?

00:24:02.721 --> 00:24:03.721
&gt;&gt;Molly: Oh, I think this gentleman has a
question.

00:24:03.721 --> 00:24:04.721
&gt;&gt;membermale6: So, you played a teenage mother
and so I'm wondering when you were pregnant

00:24:04.721 --> 00:24:05.721
with your first child, did you ever think
back on that movie and did anything seem to

00:24:05.721 --> 00:24:06.721
be particularly realistic? Did some things
make sense or some unrealistic? Do you have

00:24:06.721 --> 00:24:20.680
any thoughts about that?

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:31.710
&gt;&gt;Molly: Well, I think everyone is different
in how they deliver their children. As I remember,

00:24:31.710 --> 00:24:35.010
I haven't seen that movie in a long time,
but I remember I did a lot of yelling and

00:24:35.010 --> 00:24:36.010
screaming.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:37.370
[laughter]

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:41.750
As most people do when they, when they have
that, that scene when they're delivering children,

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:44.350
you know, there's like [heavy panting], you
know all of that--

00:24:44.350 --> 00:24:45.350
[laughter]

00:24:45.350 --> 00:24:51.700
and I, and I did that and it seemed very realistic
at the time, but, but having had three children

00:24:51.700 --> 00:24:56.370
now I, I didn't deliver at all that way. Not
to say that it didn't hurt, because it did

00:24:56.370 --> 00:25:02.480
a lot, but all of my energy was very internal
and very, y-, you know, I felt like I couldn't

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:07.370
make that much noise because I, I would lose
my concentration and all I was focused on

00:25:07.370 --> 00:25:12.470
was getting this baby out. So, you know, if
I had to do it over again I might have played

00:25:12.470 --> 00:25:16.970
that scene a little differently, so yes, to
answer your question, I would, I would've

00:25:16.970 --> 00:25:17.970
done it differently.

00:25:17.970 --> 00:25:19.320
[laughter]

00:25:19.320 --> 00:25:21.039
Yes.

00:25:21.039 --> 00:25:26.800
&gt;&gt;memberfemale8: So, when, oh thanks. So,
when writing this book was there any one particular

00:25:26.800 --> 00:25:31.690
chapter that was your favorite writing, or,
I guess I'm just reading through it and I'm

00:25:31.690 --> 00:25:37.740
like, "She gives good email." That's an interesting
one, but I, I, my question is like, which

00:25:37.740 --> 00:25:39.799
one was your favorite in writing, if you had
one or if there's one that, like, sticks out

00:25:39.799 --> 00:25:40.799
the most?

00:25:40.799 --> 00:25:43.909
&gt;&gt;Molly: Well, when I had the, the concept
for the book, like I said I wanted to write

00:25:43.909 --> 00:25:49.760
this sort of girlfriends guide to being a
stylish woman and I, I feel like, so many

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:54.600
people feel like they grew up with me because
they kinda did, you know? My movies are sort

00:25:54.600 --> 00:26:01.130
of a rite of passage, you know, for, for so
many people. So, I, I had the idea. I knew

00:26:01.130 --> 00:26:06.440
I wanted it to be illustrated and I was really
fortunate enough to get my dream illustrator,

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:10.450
Ruben Toledo, to, to illustrate the book.

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:15.740
But I, I always knew that I wanted it to be
part narrative about my life, about my friends

00:26:15.740 --> 00:26:21.149
lives and then I also wanted it to have sort
of an advice aspect to it because I've always

00:26:21.149 --> 00:26:26.799
been sort of like the go-to girl for all of
my, my girlfriends. But I found that all of

00:26:26.799 --> 00:26:32.809
the narrative was so much easier to write.
You know, all the story telling, the, you

00:26:32.809 --> 00:26:37.531
know, and I think that has to do with my background
as an actor and getting into characters and

00:26:37.531 --> 00:26:43.130
telling stories. When it, when it actually
got to the advice part, even though I have

00:26:43.130 --> 00:26:46.279
been that advice kind of girl, it, it is sort
of hard.

00:26:46.279 --> 00:26:52.059
Once you put things down on, on paper, I didn't
want anyone to feel like I was a big old know-it-all,

00:26:52.059 --> 00:26:57.750
you know? And all of these, all of, all of
the advice that I write is really just, you

00:26:57.750 --> 00:27:01.590
know, I'm not an expert in any of the, this
is just strictly my opinion, you know? I have

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:05.220
a whole chapter we were just talking about
that on, on t-shirts.

00:27:05.220 --> 00:27:07.140
[Molly laughs]

00:27:07.140 --> 00:27:12.179
I have a whole sort of manifesto on "You're
not a billboard." And that, and that, you

00:27:12.179 --> 00:27:16.919
know, we, we shouldn't be advertising other
people's, you know, mostly it's those horrible

00:27:16.919 --> 00:27:22.029
slogans or those, you know, those t-shirts
that you pick up on vacation that say, "Barbados,"

00:27:22.029 --> 00:27:23.029
you know?

00:27:23.029 --> 00:27:24.029
[laughter]

00:27:24.029 --> 00:27:28.330
And it's like, what is this really telling
the world, you know? But anyway, to answer

00:27:28.330 --> 00:27:34.700
your question, I think, I think all of the
parts, the, the stories about, about my friends

00:27:34.700 --> 00:27:38.110
or, you know, about my life, I think those
were the definitely, or, or the one that I

00:27:38.110 --> 00:27:42.080
read to you about being a little girl and,
and sticking a stocking on my head, I think

00:27:42.080 --> 00:27:44.299
those were the most fun to write.

00:27:44.299 --> 00:27:45.299
Yes.

00:27:45.299 --> 00:27:56.020
&gt;&gt;memberfemale9: So, I have a email question.
So, like for me, being almost 40, the most

00:27:56.020 --> 00:27:59.320
disturbing thing is now I see teenagers, like,
dressing like the 80s and now I'm like that

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:03.490
old person, you know, who their era has come
back, right?

00:28:03.490 --> 00:28:04.490
[laughter]

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:08.200
It's really weird because I feel like some
of the kids; they just could've gone to my

00:28:08.200 --> 00:28:10.070
high school. Like, it looks--

00:28:10.070 --> 00:28:12.490
&gt;&gt;Molly: Yeah.

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:15.111
&gt;&gt;memberfemale9: exactly the same. So, they
say that if you are old enough to wear the

00:28:15.111 --> 00:28:18.490
fashion the first time around, you shouldn't
wear it the second time around.

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:19.490
[laughter]

00:28:19.490 --> 00:28:20.490
&gt;&gt;Molly: I disagree.

00:28:20.490 --> 00:28:21.779
&gt;&gt;memberfemale9: Ok.

00:28:21.779 --> 00:28:26.700
&gt;&gt;Molly: I respectfully disagree with that.
I, you know, I, I think that you shouldn't

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:32.340
dress head to toe in, in anything that you
wore. I mean, mostly because it probably doesn't

00:28:32.340 --> 00:28:37.880
fit, you know? I mean, I still have clothes
that I wore in the 80s, but, you know, most

00:28:37.880 --> 00:28:41.350
of them don't, don't fit the same. I mean,
I'm hanging onto them, you know, for, for

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:47.270
my kids and, you know, but, but I think, I
think the 80s now that, that people, I think

00:28:47.270 --> 00:28:53.340
there's kind of like, cherry picking the best
parts of, of a particular era, you know? There's

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:58.830
certain 80s-esque things that I wear now,
you know, sort of color choices. I mean, Google,

00:28:58.830 --> 00:29:03.220
very 80s, you know? All of the, you know,
all of the primary color, the yellow and the,

00:29:03.220 --> 00:29:07.350
you know. Like, I find myself doing that now.
I have a cu-, a pair of, you know, yellow

00:29:07.350 --> 00:29:12.350
Ray bans, you know? Different, you know, hats
or, you know, there's certain things that

00:29:12.350 --> 00:29:16.630
I, that I associate with the 80s that I still
wear, but I try to make it modern, it's not

00:29:16.630 --> 00:29:17.649
just head to toe.

00:29:17.649 --> 00:29:21.980
And, you know, to be perfectly honest, in
the 80s, I was doing other eras, you know?

00:29:21.980 --> 00:29:25.890
I, I was doing, that was my version of the
20s, you know? Or, you could say that the

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:31.510
shoulder pads from the 80s was, was inspired
by the 40s. I remember in the 70s being obsessed

00:29:31.510 --> 00:29:35.580
with the 50s, you know? With Grease and everything
and, and thinking that the 50s were just the

00:29:35.580 --> 00:29:40.230
coolest thing ever. So, I think all those
fashion, it just, it's constantly re-, recirculating.

00:29:40.230 --> 00:29:44.840
There's nothing really original except for
the way that you interpret it.

00:29:44.840 --> 00:29:47.740
&gt;&gt;memberfemale9: Wow, I, great answer.

00:29:47.740 --> 00:29:48.899
[Molly laughs]

00:29:48.899 --> 00:29:51.220
I'm impressed, thank you.

